If $-1$ occurs, there is one all-even parity assignment and $\ell$ valid odd-$-1$ assignments:

$$\boxed{\text{answer}=2^{n-d}(\ell+1)}.$$

Here $d$ is the number of all distinct array values, including $-1$ when present.

For example, in $[-1,1,1,2,3]$, we have $d=4$, so $B=2^{5-4}=2$. The consecutive positive pairs are $(1,2)$ and $(2,3)$, hence $\ell=2$ and the answer is $2(2+1)=6$.

## Algorithm

Scan the already sorted array and count:

- $d$, the number of distinct-value groups;
- whether $-1$ occurs;
- $\ell$, the number of transitions between distinct positive values whose difference is exactly one.

Then apply the formula above using precomputed powers of two modulo $10^9+7$.

## Correctness proof

For positive-only selections, the pairing argument proves that alternating sum zero is equivalent to every value group having even selected size.

With an even number of selected $-1$s, those elements cancel and do not reverse the positive signs, so the same all-even condition is necessary and sufficient.

With an odd number of selected $-1$s, the total is zero exactly when the positives have usual alternating sum $-1$. The odd-group expansion proves this happens exactly when one occurring pair $(v,v+1)$ has odd counts and every other positive group has an even count.

Every fixed parity assignment has $2^{n-d}$ index subsets. Hence the algorithm counts one such assignment without $-1$, or $\ell+1$ disjoint assignments when $-1$ exists. Therefore the returned formula counts every valid subsequence exactly once.

## Complexity

